How to read this — the dependency chain

These concepts build on each other. Each one unlocks the next. The tags show you exactly why each concept matters for your job.

foundation breaks everything if missing
k8s debug needed to debug kubernetes
aws needed to design aws infra
incident needed in production incidents
Part 1 — Linux internals (week 1)
Why this matters: Every container is just a Linux process. When a K8s pod crashes, you're debugging a process. When a pipeline hangs, it's a stuck process. If you don't understand PIDs, parent/child relationships, and signals — you're guessing, not debugging.
1
Run
ps aux
and
pstree
. Find the parent of your shell. Trace back to PID 1 (init/systemd).
2
Run a sleep process in background. Find its PID. Send
SIGTERM
then
SIGKILL
. Understand the difference — one can be caught, one cannot.
3
Run a Docker container. On the host, run
ps aux | grep
to find the container's process. It's just a process — no magic.
4
Use
/proc/[PID]/
to inspect a running process — its open files, environment, memory maps.
Can you explain: Why does killing a parent process sometimes kill children? What is a zombie process and when does it happen?
Why this matters: Docker and Kubernetes are not magic. They are Linux namespaces (isolation) + cgroups (resource limits). If you understand these two primitives, you can explain every container behaviour — including why a container "thinks" it's the only thing running, and why resource limits in K8s work the way they do.
1
Run
lsns
to list all namespaces on your machine. Run a container and compare — see the new PID, net, and mount namespaces created.
2
Use
unshare --pid --fork --mount-proc bash
to manually create a new PID namespace. Run
ps aux
inside — only your bash shows up. You just made a container manually.
3
Find the cgroup for a running Docker container under
/sys/fs/cgroup/
. Read its memory limit. Change it with
docker update --memory
and watch the cgroup file update.
4
Set a K8s pod with a 50m CPU limit. Stress it. Watch
kubectl top pod
and explain why it throttles but doesn't die.
Can you explain: What is the difference between a namespace and a cgroup? Why does a container see PID 1 for its own process?
Why this matters: Logs are file descriptors. Pipelines pipe stdout to stdin. A CI step failing silently is often a file descriptor issue. "Too many open files" errors in production are FD exhaustion. This is the plumbing behind everything.
1
Run a process. Use
ls -la /proc/[PID]/fd/
to see all its open file descriptors. Identify stdin (0), stdout (1), stderr (2), plus any open files/sockets.
2
Reproduce "too many open files": write a script that opens 1000 files without closing them. Watch
ulimit -n
and understand how to change it.
3
Trace a real pipeline:
cat file | grep pattern | wc -l
. Draw what the kernel is doing — three processes, two pipes, how data flows.
4
Redirect stderr to a file, stdout to another. Then redirect both to the same file. Explain the order of operations and why
2>&1
position matters.
Can you explain: Why does command > file 2>&1 work differently from command 2>&1 > file?
Why this matters: Every production incident starts with "the server is slow." If you can't read a load average or interpret top, you can't diagnose anything. This is the first thing you check during any incident.
1
Use
top
, then
htop
. Understand every column — what is %wa (iowait)? What does a high load average with low CPU mean? (Answer: I/O wait or too many processes in D state.)
2
Use
vmstat 1
during a stress test. Read the 'b' (blocked) and 'wa' columns. Understand what they tell you.
3
Use
iostat -x 1
to find a disk-bound process. Use
iotop
to identify which process is causing it.
4
Use
free -h
and understand the difference between used, available, and cached memory. Why is "used" memory not always a problem?
Can you explain: A server has load average 8.0 on a 4-core machine but CPU is only 20%. What's happening and how do you find the cause?
Part 2 — Networking (week 2)
Why this matters: Every microservice call, every kubectl command, every Terraform API call is TCP. Security groups, NACLs, and K8s network policies are all filtering TCP. If you can't explain the three-way handshake and connection states, you can't design or debug any networked system.
1
Run
tcpdump -i any port 80
while doing
curl http://example.com
. Watch the SYN → SYN-ACK → ACK handshake in real packets.
2
Run
ss -tnp
to see all TCP connections and their states. Find a connection in ESTABLISHED, TIME_WAIT, and CLOSE_WAIT. Explain what each state means.
3
Deliberately connect to a closed port. Capture the RST packet with tcpdump. Now connect to a firewall-blocked port — notice the difference (RST vs silence/timeout).
4
Use
curl -v
and watch the full connection lifecycle — DNS, TCP connect, TLS handshake, HTTP request, response. Map each line to the TCP/IP layer it operates on.
Can you explain: A service times out vs connection refused — what does each tell you about where the failure is?
Why this matters: In Kubernetes, CoreDNS resolves service names. In AWS, Route53 resolves everything. 80% of "I can't connect to service X" issues are actually DNS issues. The engineer who understands DNS resolution is the one who solves incidents fastest.
1
Use
dig google.com
and read the full output. Understand the QUESTION, ANSWER, and AUTHORITY sections. What is the TTL?
2
Trace a DNS resolution:
dig +trace google.com
. Watch it go from root servers → TLD → authoritative. Understand the chain of trust.
3
In a running K8s pod, run
cat /etc/resolv.conf
. Understand the search domains. Then do
dig kubernetes.default.svc.cluster.local
and explain what each part of that name means.
4
Simulate a DNS failure: in a K8s pod, try to reach a service by IP vs by name. Use
kubectl exec
+
nslookup
to debug CoreDNS. This is a real interview scenario.
Can you explain: A K8s pod can reach 8.8.8.8 but not a service in the same cluster. Walk through your diagnosis steps.
Part 3 — applied to real K8s + AWS debugging (week 3)
Why this matters: This is the senior interview scenario. "A request is failing — walk me through how you'd debug it." If you can trace the path from internet → DNS → ALB → K8s ingress → service → pod, you can answer any debugging question.
1
Deploy a simple app on EKS with an ALB ingress. Then break it 5 different ways: wrong DNS, wrong security group, wrong target group, pod crash, wrong port. Debug each using only fundamentals.
2
Use
kubectl exec
into a pod and run
curl
,
nslookup
,
wget
against other services. Build a mental model of what can reach what and why.
3
Add a network policy that blocks all ingress. Watch things break. Add rules back one by one until it works. Explain every rule in plain English.
4
Draw the network path of a request on paper — every hop, every security check, every DNS lookup — before you build it. Then build it and verify your drawing was correct.
The final test: A colleague says "users are getting 503 errors." You have 10 minutes. Walk through your diagnosis out loud, step by step, without opening any documentation. If you can do this — you're ready.
